{
  "texts": [
    "Let (V, Θ, F) be a Stokes-filtered local system on (P 1, ∞) with irregular class Θ, and let V 0 → ∂ be the corresponding formal local system (obtained by taking the associated graded on ∂).",
    "Then any direction θ ∈ ∂ that is not a singular direction determines a preferred isomorphism V | S ∼ = V 0 | S on a sufficiently small neighbourhood S ⊂ ∂ of θ, which consequently gives a splitting of the Stokes filtration",
    "Remark 4.4.",
    "The right-hand side of (3) needs some explanation: In order to restrict V 0 to I ⊂ I, we consider the I-graded local system V 0 as a local system on the covering space I (as explained in §2.2).",
    "The restriction V 0 | I then has to be understood as a local system on S again via the homeomorphism π| I: I ∼ → S for any I ∈ π 0 (π -1 (S))."
  ]
}